media.title: Banana connector
media.description: A banana connector (commonly banana plug for the male, banana socket or banana jack for the female) is a single-wire (one conductor) electrical connector used for joining wires to equipment. The term 4¬†mm connector is also used, especially in Europe, although not all banana connectors will mate with 4¬†mm parts, and 2mm banana connectors exist. Various styles of banana plug contacts exist, all based on the concept of spring metal applying outward force into the unsprung cylindrical jack to produce a snug fit with good electrical conductivity. Common types include: a solid pin split legthwise and splayed slightly, a tip of four leaf springs, a cylinder with a single leaf spring on one side, a bundle of stiff wire, a central pin surrounded by a multiply-slitted cylinder with a central bulge, or simple sheet spring metal rolled into a nearly complete cylinder. The plugs are frequently used to terminate patch cords for electronic test equipment, while sheathed banana plugs are common on multimeter probe leads.

media.title: #38 Hacking Classic Nintendo Games with Python - Python Bytes
media.description:
Matt #1: Hacking Classic Nintendo Games with Python 


Gist: used the FCEUX (http://www.fceux.com/web/home.html) Nintendo emulator‚Äôs debugger to hex edit memory and change what‚Äôs happening during play
Hex changing is how the old school Game Genie worked
Given by my Twilio colleague Sam Agnew at PyCon 2017, and all the talks are up on YouTube
Sam was inspired by Guto Maia‚Äôs PyNES: https://gutomaia.net/pyNES/
Sam uses the Lua programming language to automate changing the Mario and Zelda‚Äôs hex values. 
He then creates a Flask app where PyCon attendees could send a text message containing a hex address and 2 digit hex value to a phone number. the input would then be read into the game as he was playing
What I particularly enjoyed about this talk is that it takes a bunch of topics that sound really complicated, like hex editing memory values, and makes it more accessible to less experienced developers because they can see the results
Follow along with this blog post: https://www.twilio.com/blog/2015/08/romram-hacking..
